  "prompt": "What are the career options for a mathematics graduate?",
  "response": "A mathematics graduate has a wide range of career options available to them. Some of the most popular and in-demand options are:\n\n1. Data analyst: A data analyst is responsible for collecting, processing, and performing statistical analyses on large datasets to help organizations make better decisions.\n\n2. Actuary: An actuary uses mathematical models to assess and manage financial risks, typically in the insurance and finance industries.\n\n3. Operations research analyst: An operations research analyst uses mathematical and analytical methods to help organizations solve problems and make better decisions.\n\n4. Statistician: A statistician uses mathematical techniques to collect, analyze, and interpret data, often working in research or academia.\n\n5. Financial analyst: A financial analyst uses mathematical models to analyze investment opportunities and make recommendations to clients or organizations.\n\n6. Teacher/professor: A mathematics graduate can also pursue a career in education, teaching mathematics at the high school or college level.\n\n7. Software engineer: A mathematics graduate can apply their problem-solving skills to computer programming, working as a software engineer to design and develop software.\n\n8. Cryptographer: A cryptographer uses mathematical algorithms to create secure codes and encryption methods to protect sensitive information.\n\n9. Research scientist: A mathematics graduate can also pursue a career in research, using their mathematical skills to contribute to advancements in various fields such as physics, biology, or computer science.\n\nThese are just a few of the many career options available to mathematics graduates. Their strong analytical and problem-solving skills make them valuable assets to many industries.",
